These are the arguments stated by the people of Lowestost, poor ten- ants of our lord the king,² [to prove] that the bailiffs ³ and burgesses of Yarmouth ought not to have a charter of franchises touching the herrings in the fair of Kirkley Road.⁴

Also that as in the time of the King Edward, the grandfather of our lord the king that now is,⁵ it was ordained in parliament by statute ⁶ that every subject of the realm should be able to buy and sel] all merchandises and vietuals without impeachment within cities, boroughs, seaports, and elsewhere, and if charters of franchises or usages or patents should have been granted to the contrary, they should be held for null, and the suit that the said bailiffs and burgesses are now bringing to have a charter contrary to the said statute is not reasonable and [is] against the said statute.

Also before this time by good deliberation of all the lords and eommons in full parliament their charter was repealed for profit of the king and com- mons of the land as was then shewn and proved in the said parliament.⁷
